[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    155[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mLocation:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Why-These-Services "AWS End User Messaging or a third-party SMS/IVR vendor for patient outreach" paragraph ("The integration boundary matters: keep PHI in HIPAA-eligible services; the patient-facing channel needs a BAA"); Why-This-Isn't-Production-Ready "Patient-facing communication channels" bullet.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    156[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The recipe correctly identifies the patient-facing communication channel as a BAA-bearing dependency and names representative vendors (CipherHealth, GetWellNetwork, Memora Health, Cipher) plus AWS End User Messaging. The framing-level treatment is correct but the architecture-level constraints are not specified: which message templates are pre-approved for PHI-bearing content (typically the symptom check-in templates and the outreach reminder templates), which require de-identified content (typically the appointment-reminder templates and the educational-content templates), how the patient-facing app/SMS/IVR vendor's data-flow boundary maps to the AWS-side services (the SMS/IVR vendor often holds patient phone numbers and message-delivery logs which are PHI), and how patient-consent capture flows through the system (patient consent for SMS communication, language preference, communication-frequency preference; opt-out handling).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    157[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    158[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mThe TCPA dimension is also implicit: SMS to patient phones requires opt-in consent under the Telephone Consumer Protection Act, the consent must be documented, and revocation must be honored. The audit-trail discipline that supports TCPA defense is a specific architectural concern.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    159[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mFix:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Expand the "AWS End User Messaging or a third-party SMS/IVR vendor" paragraph: "The patient-facing communication channel is a BAA-bearing dependency: AWS End User Messaging (formerly Pinpoint SMS and Voice) is HIPAA-eligible under the BAA when configured per BAA requirements; third-party vendors (CipherHealth, GetWellNetwork, Memora Health) require their own BAA with the hospital. The vendor holds patient phone numbers and message-delivery logs (both PHI). Pre-approve message templates by content category: symptom check-in templates and outreach reminder templates can carry minimal PHI (patient first name, post-discharge day, condition reference); appointment-reminder templates and educational-content templates use de-identified content. Patient-consent capture flows through the system as a structured event in the patient-state record (consent for SMS, preferred language, preferred channel, communication-frequency preference); opt-out handling honors revocation immediately. TCPA dimension applies to SMS to patient phones (opt-in consent required, documented, and honored on revocation); the audit trail in the worklist-audit and intervention-audit indexes supports TCPA defense."[K
