[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    161[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;143;161;179m###[38;2;192;197;206m [38;2;143;161;179mArchitecture Expert Review[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    162[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    163[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;143;161;179m####[38;2;192;197;206m [38;2;143;161;179mWhat's Done Well[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    164[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    165[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe eight-stage pipeline (streaming ingest and normalization, post-discharge patient state store, trajectory history store, feature engine, scoring service, worklist builder, care management workflow tools with intervention capture and outcome capture, monitoring and governance with periodic retraining and threshold review) is the architecturally correct factoring for a post-discharge anomaly detection system. The decision to drive scoring from two paths (event-driven re-scoring on high-importance state changes including external admissions and ED visits via DynamoDB Streams, daily-tick scoring via EventBridge) matches the operational cadence the prose describes (daily scoring with event-driven re-scoring on urgent triggers).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    166[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The streaming-vs-batch reframe in The Operational Anatomy of a Post-Discharge Episode subsection ("the pipeline has to produce useful output at every point in this timeline, not just at the moment of discharge. That's the operational requirement that makes this a streaming problem, not a batch one") is the architectural discipline most first-time builders miss; programs that build daily-batch-only systems consistently lag the day-3 to day-5 deterioration window.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    167[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The hybrid-scoring pattern in the Statistical-And-ML-Methods subsection ("combine a discharge-time risk score, a per-modality control-chart deviation score, and an engagement score. The composite ranks the worklist; the per-component scores drive the explanation") is the architectural discipline that distinguishes operationally-tunable systems from black-box deployments. Per-modality detectors (control charts on weight, BP, glucose, peak flow, symptom score) running independently with their own deviation-score outputs that feed both the composite model AND the explanation layer is the right factoring.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    168[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The capacity-aware worklist construction in Step 7 ([38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mapply_capacity_caps(sorted_rows, current_capacity())[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m) acknowledges the binding constraint the prose names ("Intervention capacity is the binding constraint"). The framing that "a model that says 'five hundred of your discharged patients are at elevated risk this week' is operationally useless unless it ranks them sharply enough that the care management team can work the top of the list and trust that the bottom is genuinely lower-priority" is operationally accurate and the architecture reflects it through capacity caps and tier-based suppression.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    169[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The intervention-capture-and-outcome-capture path closes the feedback loop with proper label-derivation discipline: "Outcomes are linked to alerts and interventions for label assembly." The pseudocode's [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mon_outcome_event[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m correctly searches for [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mrecent_scores[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m and [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mrecent_interventions[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m within an [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mOUTCOME_LINKAGE_WINDOW[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m and persists the linked label to [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mS3.PutObject(bucket = "post-discharge-training-labels", ...)[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m. This is the operationally-correct labeling path that produces the highest-quality training data.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    170[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m SageMaker Feature Store is correctly identified as the substrate for offline/online feature consistency with point-in-time correctness. SageMaker Clarify is correctly positioned for both fairness reports (subgroup-stratified) and per-prediction SHAP values that feed the explanation layer. SageMaker Model Monitor is correctly named for data drift, prediction drift, and (with labels) quality drift monitoring with the right framing for the post-discharge program: "Critical for catching the gradual drift in patient population, intervention pattern, and device firmware that affects post-discharge programs."[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    171[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The cost estimate is unusually defensible: "$1,500-4,000/month for a moderately-sized program. Outreach staffing (care managers, transitions nurses) is the dominant cost; one care manager at a typical loaded cost can cost more in a single month than the entire infrastructure. The infrastructure pays for itself if the program prevents one to two readmissions per year (typical readmission cost in the United States is in the $10,000-20,000 range depending on payer mix and condition mix)." The "infrastructure cost is a small fraction; the harder cost is people" framing is operationally accurate and is the right framing for leadership conversations.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    172[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m Implementation-time tiers (4-8 months Basic with single-cohort heart failure and Bluetooth scale RPM only, 12-18 months Production-ready with two to three cohorts and full governance, 18-36 additional months for variations) are realistic and resist optimism bias. The Production-ready tier explicitly names "randomized or matched-cohort effectiveness evaluation" as part of the production scope, which matches the recipe's Honest Take recommendation to run randomized rollouts when feasible.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    173[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The Variations and Extensions section covers eleven adjacent patterns at substantive depth (heart-failure-specific, COPD-specific, post-operative, diabetes-specific, maternal-infant, behavioral health, multi-condition longitudinal, pediatric, caregiver-focused, LLM-enhanced outreach, LLM-enhanced documentation, conversational AI patient check-ins, federated learning, patient-facing transparency, closed-loop interventions in narrow scenarios). The closed-loop framing is appropriately cautious: "Standing-order diuretic titration triggered automatically by the model in heart failure cohorts under specific conditions (within bounds, with safety features, with documented clinician oversight). Higher regulatory bar. Usually worth doing only in mature programs with strong governance."[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    174[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The Why This Isn't Production-Ready section is dense with twelve substantive bullets covering the right operational disciplines: care management governance is the program; discharge-time risk scoring as a separate prerequisite; RPM device program as a separate prerequisite with the 6-12 month rollout caveat; outreach staffing is the binding constraint; local validation against the program goal not just AUROC; causal evaluation; equity audit framework with the digital-engagement-bias amplification caveat; HIE and claims integration is a regional problem with the TEFCA-CommonWell-Carequality framing; care management workflow tool integration; patient-facing communication channels; FDA regulatory determination; documentation and reimbursement with the RPM CPT code framing; decommissioning criteria; multi-tenant and multi-cohort considerations; disaster recovery and continuity. Each bullet ties to a real production concern.[K
